==English==
===Etymology===
[[war]] + [[horse]]
===Noun===
{{en-noun}}
# {{historical}} Any horse used in horse-[[cavalry]], but especially one bearing an [[armor]]ed [[knight]].
#:''As he spoke, the knight-errant, who had remounted his '''warhorse''', galloped forward to the royal stand, with a silken kerchief bound round his wounded arm.'' — Arthur Conan Doyle, ''The White Company'', [[s:The White Company/Chapter XXIV|Chapter 26]].
# {{theater}}, {{music}} A regularly revived theatrical or musical work, as with ''[[Hamlet]]'' or a Beethoven symphony, or as excerpts thereto.
#:'''2006''' ''Most important though is the fact that, for the first time in I can barely remember how long, the ROH mounts a new production of an Italian repertory '''warhorse''' that is fully on the level of the one it replaces [and indeed, in some respects, surpasses it] [...] we actually have a "Tosca".''  — [http://groups.google.sm/group/rec.music.opera/browse_thread/thread/f6b61851eea2a30e/c9951c6fb15d3954?lnk=raot&hl=it Google group.]

